Local Storage & Session Storage in JavaScript


1Ô∏è‚É£ What is Web Storage?

Web Storage allows the browser to store data in key‚Äìvalue pairs.

There are two types:

1. localStorage
2. sessionStorage

Both store data in the browser, without a database.


2Ô∏è‚É£ localStorage

 What is localStorage?

* Stores data permanently
* Data does NOT get deleted even after:

  * Browser close
  * Tab close
  * System restart

üëâ Data stays until manually cleared.


 When to Use localStorage?

Theme preference (dark/light)
User settings
Login remember me
Cart data
Language selection


Basic localStorage Syntax

localStorage.setItem(key, value)
localStorage.getItem(key)
localStorage.removeItem(key)
localStorage.clear()

‚ö†Ô∏è Important:
localStorage stores ONLY STRINGS


Example 1: Store Data in localStorage

localStorage.setItem("username", "Vamsi");


Example 2: Get Data from localStorage

let name = localStorage.getItem("username");
console.log(name);

Output:

Vamsi


Example 3: Remove One Item

localStorage.removeItem("username");


Example 4: Clear All localStorage Data

localStorage.clear();


Example 5: Store Object in localStorage (IMPORTANT)

 Problem

localStorage cannot store objects directly.

 Solution

Convert object to JSON string.

const user = {
    name: "Vamsi",
    age: 23,
    role: "Developer"
};

localStorage.setItem("userData", JSON.stringify(user));


 Get Object Back

const data = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem("userData"));
console.log(data.name);


3Ô∏è‚É£ sessionStorage

 What is sessionStorage?

* Stores data temporarily
* Data is deleted when:

  * Browser tab is closed
  * Session ends

üëâ Works only for one tab


 When to Use sessionStorage?

OTP verification
Temporary form data
Step-by-step form progress
One-time session info


sessionStorage Syntax

sessionStorage.setItem(key, value)
sessionStorage.getItem(key)
sessionStorage.removeItem(key)
sessionStorage.clear()


Example 1: Store Data in sessionStorage

sessionStorage.setItem("sessionUser", "Vamsi");


Example 2: Get Data from sessionStorage

let user = sessionStorage.getItem("sessionUser");
console.log(user);


Example 3: Remove One Item

sessionStorage.removeItem("sessionUser");


Example 4: Clear sessionStorage

sessionStorage.clear();


Example 5: Store Object in sessionStorage

const cart = {
    product: "Laptop",
    price: 50000
};

sessionStorage.setItem("cartData", JSON.stringify(cart));


 Get Object Back

const cartData = JSON.parse(sessionStorage.getItem("cartData"));
console.log(cartData.product);


4Ô∏è‚É£ Real-Time Button Example (Local Storage)

 Scenario

* Button click count stored permanently

let count = localStorage.getItem("count") || 0;
count = Number(count);

button.addEventListener("click", () => {
    count++;
    localStorage.setItem("count", count);
    console.log("Clicked:", count);
});

üëâ Refresh page ‚Üí count remains.


5Ô∏è‚É£ Key Differences (VERY IMPORTANT)

localStorage        vs        sessionStorage
Permanent           Temporary
No expiry           Ends when tab closes
Shared across tabs  Tab-specific
Large storage       Same size


6Ô∏è‚É£ Interview One-Liners

localStorage stores data permanently in the browser.
sessionStorage stores data only for the current session.

Both store data as key-value pairs and only support strings.
